const faqItems = [
  {
    question: "Why is a used oil centrifuge a three phase centrifuge?",
    answer: "A used oil centrifuge needs to be a three-phase centrifuge to separate the water and solid particles simultaneously. A two-phase centrifuge will only separate the solids from used oil but not the water."
  },
  {
    question: "Is a used oil centrifuge same as a waste oil centrifuge?",
    answer: "A used oil centrifuge is very similar to a waste oil centrifuge. Both are three-phase centrifuges capable of separating oil from water and sludge. A used oil centrifuge may require some modifications to accommodate chemicals such as acids in the process."
  },
  {
    question: "Can used oil centrifuges separate emulsified oil?",
    answer: "A used oil centrifuge can separate oil emulsions to a certain extent. Disc stack centrifuges cannot separate chemically bonded emulsions without the use of demulsifiers."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the smallest particle a used oil centrifuge can separate?",
    answer: "A used oil centrifuge (disc-stack) can separate metal particles down to 0.5-microns. Non-metal particle separation efficiency is typically around 2-microns."
  },
  {
    question: "Do used oil centrifuges use filters or replaceable media?",
    answer: "Disc stack centrifuges for used oil do not use any filters or media. These centrifuges use the amplified force of gravity (centrifugal force) to separate water and sludge from used oil."
  },
  {
    question: "Can used oil centrifuges separate ash from used motor oil?",
    answer: "Used oil centrifuges of the disc-stack type can remove some of the ash content from used motor oil. Ash particles are microscopic carbon particles, and the centrifuge's separation ability is limited to such tiny particles separation."
  }
];

