  <p>Used oil is defined as any oil originating in crude oil or petroleum with physical or chemical impurities as contaminants from its use.</p>
  <p>The United States produces over 2 Billion gallons of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automotive_oil_recycling">used oil</a> annually. This oil has considerable value as a heating fuel and for reblending into lube oil after recycling.</p>

  <h3 id="difference-between-used-oil">Difference Between Used Oil and Waste Oil</h3>

  <p>Used oil has mineral-based origins, as in crude oil or synthetic oil. Used engine oil, transformer oil, turbine lube oil, etc., are examples of used oil.</p>
  <p>On the other hand, Waste oil is an oil with organic origin such as <a href="/wvo-centrifuge-separator/">WVO (Waste Vegetable Oil)</a>, Used Cooking Oil, yellow grease, etc.</p>

  <figure>
